election_record.label: New Jersey 1804 Electoral College

overview.note: The Federalists in New Jersey did not run a ticket for President.
The Original Election Returns for Hunterdon County uses the spelling Rozell for William Rossell and Huffty for Jacob Hufty.
The Original Election Returns for Monmouth County uses the spelling Kenny for John Kinney.

"The election for members of Congress, and the choice of Electors of President and Vice-President of the United States, was held throughout this state on Tuesday and Wednesday of last week. The candidates recommended by the late republican meeting, for each respective office, have been elected without much if any opposition. New-Jersey will therefore contribute her share in giving our country a republican President and Vice-President, an event hitherto unknown of her." The Centinel of Freedom (Newark, NJ). November 13, 1804.

The True American (Trenton, NJ), Aurora. General Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA), and The Centinel of Freedom (Newark, NJ), December 4: "As it may gratify our readers in this and other States, we publish the number of votes given at the late Congressional and Electoral election in this State for each of the Candidates agreed upon at the Republican Convention ... Republican Electoral Ticket ... No other Republican Candidate had more than 6 votes.--It appears that no Federal Ticket for Electors was formed--the highest federal Candidate having but 19 votes." The Centinel of Freedom (Newark, NJ). December 4, 1804.
